About Dataset

Definition and explanations: 8. Gapminder Data: https://www.gapminder.org/

  1. Indicator #1 Name: Indicator age of marriage.
    1. Definition of the indicator: Mean age at 1st marriage of women: The average age, in years, of first marriage for women. Women who never married are excluded. Cohabitation is excluded. The data are based on multple sources and definitions might vary.
    2. Source organization(s): Gapminder has compiled the data you see in this graph from several sources, such as official international statistics, various historical sources and our own estimates.
    3. Dataset consists data of year 2005.
  2. Indicator #2 Name: Indicator total fertility.
    1. Definition of the indicator: Children per woman (total fertility): The number of children that would be born to each woman with prevailing age-specific fertility rates.
    2. Source organization(s): The data was compiled by Gapminder, using a variety of sources: (1) UN data (most observations after 1950), (2) Figures from historical demography, these are based on actual figures of total fertility rates, (3) Estimates based on Crude Birth Rates or Princeton If, (4) Rough estimates based on extrapolations in time, extrapolations from local samples, regional averages etc.
    3. Dataset consists data of year 2005.

Overview of the Data

Using the mean age at 1st marriage of women Gapminder data set, some exploratory graphics were built to understand if it has any correlation to the number of children that would be born to each woman.

Loading libraries:

library(gridExtra)

Data Exploration

Creating a scatterplot of mean age at 1st marriage versus the number of children that would be born to each woman.

ggplot(aes(x=dtm$Age, y=dtm$Children), data = dtm)+
  geom_point(color = 'red',shape = 1)+
  xlab('Mean age at 1st marriage')+
  ylab('Number of children that would be born')

Adjusting the transparency of the points and add a linear model to the plot.

ggplot(aes(x=dtm$Age, y=dtm$Children), data = dtm)+
  geom_point(alpha = 1/2, color= 'blue')+
  xlab('Mean age at 1st marriage')+
  ylab('Number of children that would be born')+
  geom_smooth(method = 'lm', color = 'red')

Use scale_x_continuous() with the breaks parameter to adjust the x-axis: mark the x-axis every 2 units.

range(dtm$Age)
## [1] 17.60020 33.26954
ggplot(aes(x=dtm$Age, y=dtm$Children), data = dtm)+
  geom_point(color = 'purple', size = 2)+
  xlab('Mean age at 1st marriage')+
  ylab('Number of children that would be born')+
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(17,34,2))

Calculating the Pearson correlation.

cor <- cor.test(dtm$Age, dtm$Children, method = c("pearson"))
cor
